06/jenglgermphil.113.2.0131 }}\n*{{citation |title=The Date of Durham (''Carmen de Situ Dunelmi'') |author=Offler, H. S. |journal=[[Journal of English and Germanic Philology]] |year=1962 |volume=61 |issue = 3|pages=591\u201394 |jstor = 27714086}}\n*{{citation |author1=Story, Joanna |author2=Bailey, Richard N.  |title=The skull of Bede |journal=[[Antiquaries Journal]] |volume=95 |pages=325\u201350 |year=2015 |doi=10.1017/S0003581515000244 }}\n*{{citation |author=[[Benedicta Ward|Ward, Benedicta]] |title=The Venerable Bede |publisher=Geoffrey Chapman |edition=2nd |year=1998 |isbn=9780225668599 }}\n\n<!--Note about defaultsort: He is generally referred to as Alfred, not by surname-->\n[[Category:11th-century English clergy]]\n[[Category:People from Durham, England]]\n[[Category:People from Hexham]]\n[[Category:Christian relics]]\n[[Category:Bede]]\n[[Category:Collectors]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Westou"}
{"title_page": "Bruce Whitehead", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=Bruce Whitehead\n| image name=Colorado-Bruce-Whitehead.JPG\n| state_senate=Colorado\n| state=Colorado\n| district=[[Colorado's 6th Senate district|6th]]\n| term_start=August 17, 2009<ref name=\"senjournal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/Clics/CLICS2010A/csljournals.nsf/(jousen)/82B2E43E2B194EEF872576A200590CB8/$FILE/jour_001.pdf |title=Senate Journal - January 13, 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-14 |format=pdf |work=Colorado General Assembly }}</ref>\n|term_end = January 12, 2011\n| preceded=[[Jim Isgar]]\n| succeeded=[[Ellen Roberts]]\n| birth_date= \n| birth_place= [[Fort Collins, Colorado]]<ref name = \"DH\" />\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse= first name: Becca<ref name = \"DH\" />\n| profession= Engineer<ref name = \"DH\" />\n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n'''Bruce Whitehead''' is a legislator in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]]. Appointed to the [[Colorado State Senate]] as a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]] in 2009, Whitehead represented [[Colorado's 6th Senate district|Senate District 6]], which covers much of south-western Colorado, encompassing Archuleta, Dolores, La Plata, Montezuma, Montrose, Ouray, San Juan, and San Miguel counties, until 2011.<ref name = \"DH\">[http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2010/10/20/Whitehead_wants_a_full_term/ \"Whitehead wants a full term\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312102024/http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2010/10/20/Whitehead_wants_a_full_term/ |date=2012-03-12 }} article by Garrett Andrews in the ''[[Durango Herald]]'' October 20, 2010, accessed October 20, 2010</ref><ref name=\"map\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comaps.org/distsd06.html|title=State Senate District 6|accessdate=2009-12-03|work=COMaps|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108035457/http://www.comaps.org/distsd06.html|archivedate=2009-11-08}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nSenator Bruce Whitehead is a fourth generation Coloradoan born in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> Senator Whitehead obtained a B.S. in [[Civil Engineering]] in 1981 from [[Colorado State University]], and is a licensed Professional [[Engineer]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> After working in the [[Colorado Department of Natural Resources|Colorado Division of Water Resources]] office in [[Alamosa, Colorado]] he transferred to [[Durango, Colorado]] where he served as division engineer for Water District 7 administering water rights in that area of southwestern Colorado.<ref name = \"DH\" /> While in Durango he served on the boards of the Animas-La Plata Water Conservancy District, the Colorado Water Conservation District, and as director of the Southwestern Water Conservation District.<ref name = \"DH\" />  He was appointed to the Colorado State Senate by Governor [[Bill Ritter]] to fill the vacant position of Democrat [[Jim Isgar]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> He was sworn in as State Senator for District 6 on August 17, 2009 by Colorado Supreme Court Justice [[Gregory J. Hobbs, Jr.|Greg Hobbs]]. Committee assignments include the Senate Agriculture, Livestock and Natural Resource Committee where he serves as Vice-Chair. He also serves on the Transportation committee. He also serves on the Interim Water Resources Review Committee, the UMTRA Oversight Committee where he serves as the Chair, and was also appointed as the Senate Ag Committee representative on the Inter-Basin Compact Committee (IBCC). Whitehead has an extensive background in Colorado water issues.<ref name = \"DH\" /> The latter part of his career with the State of Colorado was in the capacity of Division Engineer for the [[San Juan River (Colorado River)|San Juan River]] and [[Dolores River]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> Prior to his appointment to the Senate, Bruce was a Director on the Colorado Water Conservation Board representing southwestern [[Colorado]]. He has retired from the Colorado Division of Water Resources but continues to work part-time for the Southwestern Water Conservation District<ref name = \"DH\" /> and is continuing to serve as an Engineer Adviser for the Upper Colorado River Commission.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nHe and his wife Becca<ref name = \"DH\" /> enjoy the arts and the outdoors, and live south of Hesperus near Breen. They are raising two daughters, Isabel and Risa.<ref name = \"DH\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.coloradosenate.org/home/ Colorado State Senate Democratic Majority]\n\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehead, Bruce}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colorado Democrats]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=Bruce Whitehead\n| image name=Colorado-Bruce-Whitehead.JPG\n| state_senate=Colorado\n| state=Colorado\n| district=6th\n| term_start=August 17, 2009<ref name=\"senjournal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/Clics/CLICS2010A/csljournals.nsf/(jousen)/82B2E43E2B194EEF872576A200590CB8/$FILE/jour_001.pdf |title=Senate Journal - January 13, 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-14 |format=pdf |work=Colorado General Assembly }}</ref>\n|term_end = January 12, 2011\n| preceded=[[Jim Isgar]]\n| succeeded=[[Ellen Roberts]]\n| birth_date= \n| birth_place= [[Fort Collins, Colorado]]<ref name = \"DH\" />\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse= first name: Becca<ref name = \"DH\" />\n| profession= Engineer<ref name = \"DH\" />\n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n'''Bruce Whitehead''' is a legislator in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]]. Appointed to the [[Colorado State Senate]] as a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]] in 2009, Whitehead represents Senate District 6, which covers much of south-western Colorado, encompassing Archuleta, Dolores, La Plata, Montezuma, Montrose, Ouray, San Juan, and San Miguel counties.<ref name = \"DH\">[http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2010/10/20/Whitehead_wants_a_full_term/ \"Whitehead wants a full term\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312102024/http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2010/10/20/Whitehead_wants_a_full_term/ |date=2012-03-12 }} article by Garrett Andrews in the ''[[Durango Herald]]'' October 20, 2010, accessed October 20, 2010</ref><ref name=\"map\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comaps.org/distsd06.html|title=State Senate District 6|accessdate=2009-12-03|work=COMaps|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108035457/http://www.comaps.org/distsd06.html|archivedate=2009-11-08}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nSenator Bruce Whitehead is a fourth generation Coloradoan born in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> Senator Whitehead obtained a B.S. in [[Civil Engineering]] in 1981 from [[Colorado State University]], and is a licensed Professional [[Engineer]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> After working in the [[Colorado Department of Natural Resources|Colorado Division of Water Resources]] office in [[Alamosa, Colorado]] he transferred to [[Durango, Colorado]] where he served as division engineer for Water District 7 administering water rights in that area of southwestern Colorado.<ref name = \"DH\" /> While in Durango he served on the boards of the Animas-La Plata Water Conservancy District, the Colorado Water Conservation District, and as director of the Southwestern Water Conservation District.<ref name = \"DH\" />  He was appointed to the Colorado State Senate by Governor [[Bill Ritter]] to fill the vacant position of Democrat [[Jim Isgar]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> He was sworn in as State Senator for District 6 on August 17, 2009 by Colorado Supreme Court Justice [[Gregory J. Hobbs, Jr.|Greg Hobbs]]. Committee assignments include the Senate Agriculture, Livestock and Natural Resource Committee where he serves as Vice-Chair. He also serves on the Transportation committee. He also serves on the Interim Water Resources Review Committee, the UMTRA Oversight Committee where he serves as the Chair, and was also appointed as the Senate Ag Committee representative on the Inter-Basin Compact Committee (IBCC). Whitehead has an extensive background in Colorado water issues.<ref name = \"DH\" /> The latter part of his career with the State of Colorado was in the capacity of Division Engineer for the [[San Juan River (Colorado River)|San Juan River]] and [[Dolores River]].<ref name = \"DH\" /> Prior to his appointment to the Senate, Bruce was a Director on the Colorado Water Conservation Board representing southwestern [[Colorado]]. He has retired from the Colorado Division of Water Resources but continues to work part-time for the Southwestern Water Conservation District<ref name = \"DH\" /> and is continuing to serve as an Engineer Adviser for the Upper Colorado River Commission.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nHe and his wife Becca<ref name = \"DH\" /> enjoy the arts and the outdoors, and live south of Hesperus near Breen. They are raising two daughters, Isabel and Risa.<ref name = \"DH\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.coloradosenate.org/home/ Colorado State Senate Democratic Majority]\n\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehead, Bruce}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colorado Democrats]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Blizzardwind", "label": "safe", "comment": "added senate district links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruce_Whitehead"}
{"title_page": "Star Theatres", "text_new": "[[Image:starlogo.jpg|right]]\n'''Star Theatres''' was a [[movie theatre]] chain owned and operated by [[Loews Cineplex Entertainment]] and [[AMC Theatres]].  Based solely in [[Michigan]], Star was known for having extravagant interior designs, many screens, and in some cases, stadium-style seating. The chain made the Summer 1990 [[Entertainment Weekly]] Honor Roll for movie theaters with the late [[Detroit Free Press]] critic Kathy Huffhines declaring, \"IT'S FRIENDLY, kicky, and cute and looks like a bright red-and-white jukebox from the outside.\"<ref> Entertainment Weekly, June 28, July 5, 1991 p. 26 </ref>\n\nThe chain came to prominence in the late 1980s and early 1990s as more audiences chose to view films at a [[megaplex]]. Over time, some locations shut down or moved, while others thrived. The [[Southfield, Michigan]] and [[Great Lakes Crossing|Auburn Hills, Michigan]] locations were considered the [[flagships]] of the chain and still remain very popular with local movie-goers, but were rebranded as AMC theatres in 2018. The slogan was \"Love*Laugh*Live\" and \"Larger than Life\".{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn 2018, all locations were rebranded as AMC theatres. The Southfield location was permanently closed in 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Locations ==\n*AMC Star Southfield 20 - [[Southfield, MI]] (opened June 1997, closed 2020)\n*AMC Star Gratiot 21 - [[Clinton Township, Macomb County, Michigan|Clinton Township, MI]] (opened 1990)\n*Star Holland 8 - [[Holland, MI]] (opened 1989)\n*Star Lincoln Park 8 - [[Lincoln Park Shopping Center]], [[Lincoln Park, MI]] (opened May 1988, closed 2003, demolished 2018)\n*AMC Fairlane 21 - [[Fairlane Town Center]], [[Dearborn, MI]] (opened May 2000 as Star Fairlane 21)\n*AMC Grand Rapids 18 - [[Grand Rapids, MI]] (opened 1992 as Star Grand Rapids 18)\n*AMC Star Great Lakes 25 - [[Great Lakes Crossing Outlets]], [[Auburn Hills, MI]] (opened April 1999)\n*Star Rochester Hills 10 - [[Rochester Hills, MI]] (opened 1989, closed and sold 2010, remodeled into a location of an [[Emagine Entertainment|Emagine]] theatre)\n*Star Taylor 10 - [[Taylor, MI]] (opened 1989, closed 2009, reopened 2010 as Spotlight Theaters Taylor; 2012 Spotlight Theaters in Taylor has closed)\n*AMC John R 15 - [[Madison Heights, MI]] (opened 1989 as Star John R 15)\n*Star Winchester - Winchester Mall, [[Rochester Hills, MI]] (opened 1985, closed 1999, rebuilt into a strip mall)\n\n{{Wanda Group}}\n\n[[Category:Movie theatre chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:AMC Theatres]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:starlogo.jpg|right]]\n'''Star Theatres''' was a [[movie theatre]] chain owned and operated by [[Loews Cineplex Entertainment]] and [[AMC Theatres]].  Based solely in [[Michigan]], Star was known for having extravagant interior designs, many screens, and in some cases, stadium-style seating. The chain made the Summer 1990 [[Entertainment Weekly]] Honor Roll for movie theaters with the late [[Detroit Free Press]] critic Kathy Huffhines declaring, \"IT'S FRIENDLY, kicky, and cute and looks like a bright red-and-white jukebox from the outside.\"<ref> Entertainment Weekly, June 28, July 5, 1991 p. 26 </ref>\n\nThe chain came to prominence in the late 1980s and early 1990s as more audiences chose to view films at a [[megaplex]]. Over time, some locations shut down or moved, while others thrived. The [[Southfield, Michigan]] and [[Great Lakes Crossing|Auburn Hills, Michigan]] locations were considered the [[flagships]] of the chain and still remain very popular with local movie-goers, but were rebranded as AMC theatres in 2018. The slogan was \"Love*Laugh*Live\" and \"Larger than Life\".{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn 2018, all locations were rebranded as AMC theatres.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Locations ==\n*AMC Star Southfield 20 - [[Southfield, MI]] (opened June 1997, closed 2020)\n*AMC Star Gratiot 21 - [[Clinton Township, Macomb County, Michigan|Clinton Township, MI]] (opened 1990)\n*Star Holland 8 - [[Holland, MI]] (opened 1989)\n*Star Lincoln Park 8 - [[Lincoln Park Shopping Center]], [[Lincoln Park, MI]] (opened May 1988, closed 2003, demolished 2018)\n*AMC Fairlane 21 - [[Fairlane Town Center]], [[Dearborn, MI]] (opened May 2000 as Star Fairlane 21)\n*AMC Grand Rapids 18 - [[Grand Rapids, MI]] (opened 1992 as Star Grand Rapids 18)\n*AMC Star Great Lakes 25 - [[Great Lakes Crossing Outlets]], [[Auburn Hills, MI]] (opened April 1999)\n*Star Rochester Hills 10 - [[Rochester Hills, MI]] (opened 1989, closed and sold 2010, remodeled into a location of an [[Emagine Entertainment|Emagine]] theatre)\n*Star Taylor 10 - [[Taylor, MI]] (opened 1989, closed 2009, reopened 2010 as Spotlight Theaters Taylor; 2012 Spotlight Theaters in Taylor has closed)\n*AMC John R 15 - [[Madison Heights, MI]] (opened 1989 as Star John R 15)\n*Star Winchester - Winchester Mall, [[Rochester Hills, MI]] (opened 1985, closed 1999, rebuilt into a strip mall)\n\n{{Wanda Group}}\n\n[[Category:Movie theatre chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:AMC Theatres]]\n", "name_user": "Tkefan29", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_Theatres"}
